.TH INCLUDES 1 "March 2026" "includes"
.SH NAME
includes \- resolve C/C++ #include dependencies

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B includes
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fISOURCES...\fR

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B includes
parses C/C++ source files, evaluates preprocessor conditionals, resolves
.BR #include
directives, and prints the set of headers or mapped source files they depend on.

It understands \fB#if\fR, \fB#ifdef\fR, \fB#ifndef\fR, \fB#elif\fR, \fB#else\fR and
\fB#endif\fR, evaluates expressions (including \fBdefined(X)\fR), and follows
typical compiler search rules for quoted vs angled includes.

By default, it prints a (possibly deduplicated) list of include paths, one per
line.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI "-I " PATH
Add an include search path.

.TP
.BI "-T " TOOLKIT
Select compiler toolkit; currently \fBgcc\fR and \fBmsc\fR are recognized.

.TP
.BI "-t " TRIPLET
Target triplet (for example \fBx86_64-linux-gnu\fR).  If omitted, the toolkit
tries to auto-detect a sensible default.

.TP
.BI "-L " NUM
Maximum include recursion depth.  \fB0\fR means only the root source file is
parsed; \fB-1\fR (the default) means unlimited depth.

.TP
.B "-d"
Allow duplicate includes in the output.  By default, each resolved path is
printed at most once.

.TP
.B "-u"
Only output quoted includes (\fB"file"\fR).

.TP
.B "-a"
Only output angled includes (\fB<file>\fR).

.TP
.B "-A"
Recurse into angled includes as well as quoted ones.  By default, only quoted
includes are recursively followed.

.TP
.B "-p"
Preserve quotes in the output.  Without \fB-p\fR, paths are printed without
surrounding \fB"\"\fR or \fB<>\fR.  With \fB-p\fR, quoted and angled includes are
printed as they appeared in the source.

.TP
.B "-c"
Header-to-source mapping mode.  Instead of printing headers, \fBincludes\fR
tries to map each header to a corresponding C/C++ source file in the same
tree (for example \fBfoo.h\fR \-> \fBfoo.c\fR / \fBfoo.cpp\fR) and prints those
sources.

In this mode:
.RS
.IP \[bu] 2
Only headers that can be mapped to existing source files are output; missing
or unmapped headers (including standard C++ headers without extensions) are
ignored.
.IP \[bu]
The current root source file is suppressed by default; see \fB-e\fR to change
this.
.IP \[bu]
The \fB-n\fR and \fB-m\fR switches are ignored.
.RE

.TP
.B "-e"
With \fB-c\fR, also echo source files that appear on the command line.  This
causes the root translation units themselves to be included in the mapped
source list instead of being suppressed.

.TP
.B "-n"
Only output existing (resolved) include paths.  Missing includes are not
printed.  Ignored in \fB-c\fR mode.

.TP
.B "-m"
Only output missing (unresolved) include names.  Ignored in \fB-c\fR mode.

.TP
.B "-f"
Canonicalize output paths using \fBrealpath(3)\fR, producing absolute,
normalized paths.

.TP
.B "-s"
Sort output lines.

.TP
.B "-j"
Emit JSON output: a single array of string paths is printed to stdout.

.TP
.B "-g"
Emit a Graphviz \fB.dot\fR include graph, with one directed edge per include.

.TP
.B "-P"
Process multiple root sources in parallel (one thread per source).

.TP
.B "-w"
Enable parser warnings.  When set, unmatched or missing \fB#endif\fR directives
and unresolved includes are reported as warnings on stderr.  Without \fB-w\fR,
these conditions still affect the exit status (parse errors) and output
filtering, but extra warning messages are suppressed.

.TP
.B "-q"
Decrease log verbosity (only errors at the lowest level).

.TP
.B "-v"
Increase log verbosity (up to very verbose debug output).

.TP
.B "--help"
Show a short usage summary and exit.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success; all sources parsed without preprocessor errors.
.TP
.B 1
Parse error (for example, unmatched or missing \fB#endif\fR).
.TP
.B 2
File or usage error (for example, missing sources, invalid options).
.TP
.B 3
Internal error (allocation failure, toolkit failure, etc.).

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR cpp (1),
.BR gcc (1)